mnill
In reply to this message
Scalability, to achieve consensus on the state of the world and record the transitions of that state, blockchains incur a cost over traditional databases. We will overcome this cost by initially balancing what state to put on-chain and what to put in a traditional database managed by a centralized server. Over time as technologies and techniques develop, EVE Frontier will transition from centralized servers to full decentralization and on-chain provability.
12:43
In reply to this message
More specifically, we ultimately see EVE Frontier as an Ethereum-based application, leveraging the chain's strong balance between security and decentralization. However, as highlighted by the Blockchain Trilemma, Ethereum is not yet designed for scale. For context, Ethereum currently handles around 1.3 million transactions per day‚Äîbarely enough to support EVE Online‚Äôs Market System, which averages 1 million daily transactions, let alone EVE Online‚Äôs Total World State, which processes roughly 1 billion transactions per day.
In response to these limitations, we have adopted a pragmatic approach, experimenting with various strategies to build the autonomous world we envision. Initially, we worked with an Ethereum sidechain before developing our own Layer 2 scaling solution on Optimism‚Äôs OP Stack. Looking ahead, our next phase of testing will explore Redstone, another Layer 2 solution built on the OP Stack and focused on the deployment of Autonomous Worlds. We will continue to evolve our blockchain strategy, adapting to the needs of the Frontier and its community as the technology progresses and as more of the game‚Äôs fundamental logic is enshrined on-chain.
